Task 1 - Introductory Questions (10 points)

In this task you will have to answer some short questions about interpretations of regressions and R output.

1) Looking at the following output, what is the dependent variable? (2 points)

Answer: rating

2) What is the t-statistic that is missing in column (3) of the previous output? (2 points)

Answer: 9.43 (\(=\frac{-2.2128}{0.2347}\))

3) What is the null hypothesis that is being tested if you look at column (4)? (2 points)

Answer: \(H_1: \ \beta=0\)

4) Looking at the previous output, which of the following statements is/are TRUE (2 points)

Answer:

  • The association between fat and rating is negative and statistically significant at conventional levels, holding sugars constant.
  • We can reject that the coefficient for sugar is equal to 0 (at <1% significance level)

5) We want to fit the following model: \[GPA = \beta_0 + \beta_1HoursStudy + \beta_2Attendance + \beta_3Attendance \times HoursStudy + \varepsilon\]

In order to do so, we have a dataset D with all the variables in our model. Complete the following line of code: (2 points)

Answer: lm(GPA ~ Attendance*HoursStudy, data = D)

Task 2 - Let’s play some (collegiate) sports! (45 points)

In honor of the future arrival of a certain high school quarterback superstar to UT Austin, we will be looking at collegiate sports. This a million dollar industry, and it’s worth the time to look at some data and see how expenditure and revenue are related.

For this, we will be using data that comes from the Equity in Athletics Data Analysis, and put together by the #TidyTuesday team.

You can load the data using this line of code: 

library(tidyverse)
sports <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/HW1/data/sports.csv")

1) How many observations are there in the this dataset? And how many unique institutions? (3 points)

Answer:

# Number of observations:
nrow(sports)

# Number of unique institutions:
# One way:
sports %>% group_by(unitid) %>% tally() %>% nrow()

# Another way:
sports %>% group_by(unitid) %>% summarize(n = 1) %>% nrow()

# And another way:
sports %>% distinct(., unitid) %>% nrow()

# or 
nrow(distinct(sports, unitid))

# And in base:
length(unique(sports$unitid))

132327 observations and 2141 unique institutions

3) Because we are going to be looking at revenue, remove from the dataset all observations that are missing either total revenue, revenue for men, or revenue for women. How many observations do we have left? (5 points)

Answer:

# One way
sports <- sports %>% filter(!is.na(total_rev_menwomen) & !is.na(rev_men) & !is.na(rev_women))

# Another way
sports <- sports %>% drop_na(total_rev_menwomen, rev_men, rev_women)

We now have 43614 observations


4 points: Effectively removes missing values from all 3 variables

2 points: Removes some missing values, but not all/ Removes missing values for other variables as well

library(patchwork)

sports <- sports %>% mutate(total_exp_menwomen = total_exp_menwomen/1000,

    theme_minimal()

g_exp + g_rev

5) Now transform the variables into logarithms and create the same plots. What can you say now about these graphs? (1 sentence) (5 points)

Answer:

sports <- sports %>% mutate(log_total_exp = log(total_exp_menwomen),
                            log_total_rev = log(total_rev_menwomen))

g_exp <- ggplot(data = sports, aes(x = log_total_exp)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "skyblue", fill = "white", lwd = 1.1, bins = 50) +
  xlab("log(Expenditure)") + ylab("Count") +
    theme_minimal()

g_rev <- ggplot(data = sports, aes(x = log_total_rev)) +
  geom_histogram(color = "skyblue", fill = "white", lwd = 1.1, bins = 50) +
  xlab("log(Revenue)") + ylab("Count") +
    theme_minimal()

g_exp + g_rev

By transforming expenditure and revenue with log, we can see that now they look normally distributed.

6) Using the previously cleaned data, fit the following model: \[\log(TotalRevenue) = \beta_0 + \beta_1\log(TotalExpenditure) + \beta_2 Year + \varepsilon\] Fit the regression, show your results, and interpret \(\hat{\beta}_1\) (8 points)

Answer:

lm1 <- lm(log_total_rev ~ log_total_exp + year, data = sports)

summary(lm1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = log_total_rev ~ log_total_exp + year, data = sports)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -7.3787 -0.0247  0.0441  0.1102  4.7566 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value            Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)    1.4808235  2.5249638   0.586               0.558    
## log_total_exp  0.9331138  0.0013000 717.764 <0.0000000000000002 ***
## year          -0.0005673  0.0012519  -0.453               0.650    
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.3688 on 43611 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.922,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.922 
## F-statistic: 2.578e+05 on 2 and 43611 DF,  p-value: < 0.00000000000000022

Because both \(x\) and \(y\) are in \(\log()\), we can interpret this as a percentage change. Then, an increase in 1% of total expenditures is associated with an average increase of 0.93% in total revenue, holding year constant, which is statistically significant at a 1% level.


For code

3 points: Runs a linear model with all correct variables

2 points: Forgets either revenue or expenditure in log OR doesn’t add year

1 point: Forgets either revenue and expenditure in log AND doesn’t add year/ forget all logs


For interpretation

5 points: Correct interpretation (uses the right words and percentage change)

4 points: Overall correct, but it’s missing either “On average” (“mean” or “expected” will also be accepted) or “holding year constant”

3 points: Missing both “on average” and “holding year constant”

2 points: Correct wording, but doesn’t interpret percentage change correctly (change of 1% in X is associated to change in β1% in Y)

0 points: Any other case.

College-level data

Now that we have analyzed some general associations, let’s look at whether the association between revenue and expenditure is different for men and women’s sports.

For this, we will use a transformation of the previous dataset, where we will append data for men and women separately at the institution level to make the analysis easier. You can find the new dataset here:



sports_mw <- read.csv("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/maibennett/sta235/main/exampleSite/content/Assignments/Homework/HW1/data/sports_mw.csv")

In sports_mw, we have the same data as before, but at the institution-year-gender level:

variable class description
unitid integer School ID
year integer year, which is year: year + 1, eg 2015 is 2015 to 2016
women integer 1: data refers to women sports, and 0: data refers to male sports
revenue double Total revenue for all sports at the unitid-year-women level, measured in 1,000 USD
expenditure double Total expenditure for all sports at the unitid-year-women level, measured in 1,000 USD
enrollment double Enrollment at the unitid-year-women level
partic double Total participation in sports at the unitid-year-women level

This means that for each year, a specific school (let’s say, UT), will have two observations: One for women (women==1) and one for men (women==0). You can see the structure in the following example:

3) Fit the following model: \[Price = \beta_0 + \beta_1 NumRooms + \beta_2 Area + \beta_4 Pool + \beta_5 Apartment + \varepsilon\]

where Apartment is a variable the takes the value of 1 if the property is an apartment and 0 in another case.

Note: You will have to create an additional variable

a) What is the average price for a 350 sq m house with 3 rooms and a pool? (Round to the closest integer) (7 points)

Answer:

housing <- housing %>% mutate(apartment = ifelse(type_of_property=="apartment", 1, 0))

lm1 <- lm(price ~ number_of_rooms + house_area + swimming_pool + apartment, data = housing)

4) Fit the following quadratic model: (5 points)

\[Price = \beta_0 + \beta_1 Area + \beta_2 Area^2 + \varepsilon\]

a) What is the average increase/decrease in price for an extra sq meter for an average-sized unit? Round to the nearest integer (10 points)

Answer:

lm2 <- lm(price ~ house_area + I(house_area^2), data = housing)

summary(lm2)
